USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is almost strange how Barack Obama, the president who is known as the smartest, is repeating the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghanistan issue, whom he himself considered the stupidest.
When he finally expressed his long-awaited Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he had written it down on the copy paper from the Bush-Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not only does he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, he even used the name of the Bush Declaration of January 2007 as the name of his own declaration: "New Way Forward", without hesitation.
He himself criticized the Bush idea three years ago of sending fresh troop contingents to civil war-torn Iraq as "irresponsible and disastrous in its consequences".
But the following months showed that the Bush strategy, based on military recommendations, was the only possible one and was so successful that Iraq is no longer mentioned in the news.
The Bushs' reputation has not been improved by this, for objectively he has left his successor in a much more grateful starting position than was expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will be repeated.
The military has again asked him to increase the contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghanistan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who, despite his subordinationist habits, has been harshly critical of the stuttering gunmen in the White House.
He demanded 40,000 soldiers to turn the situation around.
The president hesitated for three months, but couldn't come up with a better idea, so he cheated the general out of 10,000 soldiers.
From Europe he pressed for the promise of another 5,000, although he himself originally expected at least 10,000.
The most problematic part of the Obama strategy is his plan to withdraw troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and complete the process in three years.
Some doubt that the halving of the increase will have the same effect as the measure in Iraq.
Despite the recent civil war, Iraqi society is relatively well structured, and its leaders respect the values.
The situation in Afghanistan is one of contraindications - no one can be trusted and no agreements are kept.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, who are used to changing their minds every day.
The political institutions, even if formally correctly established, remain mere shell structures, behind which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to grow.
The balance of interests between the various ethnic groups is unusually complicated, especially because of the confusion of the situation, which complicates the Pakistani and Iranian influences even further.
The construction of a 'performing state', which is the minimalist goal of the whole operation, is also very unrealistic.
The timeline of Obama's strategy alienated by his volunteerism
Over the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and now it is on the verge of explosion.
Only a truly romantic soul, unimpressed by facts, can believe that the little soldiers who have broken out in the war cry of "early homecoming" are creating a miracle here.
From a political point of view, the date for the withdrawal of troops is a complete irresponsibility, because the Taliban will take this as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in the fighting in Afghanistan is waning.
The European politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is connected with the war in the Hindukush foothills.
Another possible factor that could radically influence the situation is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions do not affect the Iranians, the United States will face a very difficult question as to whether the problem cannot be solved by troops.
That question must be answered in the period of time that America is moving forward from Obama to a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
But any solution will also mean a dramatic turnaround in the Afghan situation.
The only consolation for Barack Obama is the fact that there are still three years to go before the presidential election, and that there is enough time for him to adopt a different strategy if it turns out to be a total failure.
