Czech discovery: a substance that works on 'stolen' HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds designed to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the compound does not work as strongly on common virus variants as any of the drugs already available.
AIDS is not curable.
But the combination of drugs can prolong the life of patients and prevent the HIV virus from multiplying in the body.
But taking them is accompanied by a whole host of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of virus replication has also led to the development of resistant viruses against which medicines are no longer effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, the VSCHT (Chemical and Technological University) in Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to tackling virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances known as metallocarbons act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
The metal carbores are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the virus from multiplying in a way that is different from any drug used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists are developing new 'improved' compounds, which have been prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
The metal carbores have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-layered cages made of boron, hydrogen, and carbon atoms, linked by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Home-grown and persistent virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus splitting caused by the HIV protease, no mature infectious virus particles would form.
When we turn off the HIV protease, we also turn off the virus' growth in the patient's body, explain the scientists in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the CR Academy of Sciences.
In the paper, published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified.
Slightly weaker, but more reliable
The effects of this series of substances on HIV proteases were tested in the test tube, including against their resistant variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metallocarbons on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as in the case of the medicinal products used in clinical trials, but it does not lose its effect on the resistant variants against which the medicinal products used are often ineffective.
