Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would like to have two children and that this is also legally permissible.
But like many Chinese, they have only a modest amount of government health and life insurance.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West misjudge the one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with her first child.
Yes, we're being robbed of the ability to have more than one child.
The problem is not simply one of policy.
The problem is money.
Other couples give psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the personnel manager, said that she wanted only one child because she was an only child. "We were the center of the family and used to everyone taking care of us.
We are not used to caring for others and we do not really want to".
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old who owns a translation company, said so bluntly.
For middle-class parents with dual careers, which is causing the birth rate to drop, he said, it's about being successful and being selfish.
The group of people now aged 20 to 39 grew up watching their parents struggle during the early days of China's capitalism experiment, and they certainly don't want that kind of life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child, he said, places enormous demands on the parents' time.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there's the space question -- "You need to rebuild your apartment" -- and the life planning -- "By the time the child is nine months old, you already have a resume ready for the best preschools".
Most of his friends are willing to go through this once, Chen said, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to achieve a higher standard of living, he said.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
UN group drafts plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference - which has so far been marked by wild poses and mutual accusations - set a new focus on Friday with the release of a document that puts forward an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with the industrial nations shouldering the greatest burden in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, has both identified the remaining obstacles and indicated the way forward.
But it was seen as a major step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time, as more than 100 top politicians from around the world are arriving in Copenhagen next week.
The text, drafted by a special UN task force, does not mention the amount of money that rich countries should give to poor countries to help them cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options on key issues, including how industrial and large emerging countries can limit their carbon emissions and what the upper limit of global temperature rise should be for policymakers to support.
The process is given great flexibility, says John Coequyt, executive director of the Sierra Club of Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, has summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's top climate official, Yvo de Boer, has called "the big picture".
It outlines a possible agreement whereby the developed nations would jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, while the larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, these countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community also gave a boost to the talks on Friday by pledging $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change - from flooding and drought to forest destruction.
Friday still brought the same verbal fireworks that had determined the talks of the previous week.
The US Special Rapporteur on climate change, Todd Stern, has rejected formulations calling for binding greenhouse gas emissions reductions for developed countries, compared with voluntary reductions for larger emerging countries, if these are not financed by the industrialised nations.
This train announced that the Obama administration is taking a tougher line with China than representatives of the Bush administration did not even two years ago.
The United States will not sign a deal without major emerging markets standing up and taking action, said Stern, who also complained that the text did not go far enough to ensure that the cuts could be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei's statement that the top US climate negotiator was either lacking in "reason" or "highly irresponsible" in saying earlier this week that the United States would not financially help China to tackle global warming.
The future economic direction of the great powers is at stake, and fractures have developed both within the developed nations and between the developed and the emerging nations.
The current battle is about saving individual economies as much as saving the planet, with China and the United States fighting over their respective commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take bolder action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the great powers are fighting over who should bear the cost of curbing greenhouse gas emissions, since even affected countries have moved to be more aggressive in holding those with very high greenhouse gas emissions accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game that will develop into a new economic dominance, says Ulate, who also serves as a regional climate change advisor for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impacts of climate change indicated that they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although the leading participants say that the talks will lead to a political agreement at best.
The Alliance of Small Island States, with 43 members, presented a draft treaty of 24 pages early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said the small island nations' offensive "exerted political pressure on the entire political process", in part because they are now united and demanding action from emerging countries like China and India.
The talks gained new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that most outstanding issues must be resolved before the arrival of the Heads of Government in order to reach an agreement.
High-level officials, including Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Vice Minister, got off their planes and raced through the halls of the Bella Center for closed-door meetings and press conferences to file claims that will be negotiated over the next week.
The sheer scale of the gathering -- 13,000 people coming in and out of the convention center every day, guitar-playing activists staging late-night shows making fun of countries they think are betraying and selling, and draft contracts being hand-delivered by hand rather than e-mail -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is just building up: almost all the important ministers are here now and from Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are coming to the top, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president of global policy at Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
Britain's first 225km/h train redefines the feeling of Monday
On Monday morning at 5:13 a.m., a whistle will pierce the darkness to announce a train departure that will revolutionise British transport.
The first high-speed commuter train in the country will reach 225 km/h on its blitz from Ashford, Kent, to London St Pancras, covering 93 km in 38 minutes.
Lady Kelly Holmes will then be travelling to Lord Adonis, the Minister for Transport, on board the first Javelin commuter service from London.
He hopes that the new service will eventually link Britain to an international rail network of fast, reliable trains, and link the large metropolitan areas of the Midlands, the North and Scotland to London.
The neglected province could become a vibrant commuter town, commute times could be radically reduced, and switching from air and car to rail would reduce national carbon emissions and road congestion.
In theory, the three major parties believe in this vision.
But the many billions of British pounds needed to build a new national rail network, the inevitable planning battle and fears of environmental damage could still put the brakes on Britain's high-speed railways.
High Speed Two (HS2), a company set up in January to submit a feasibility study to the government, will deliver the report on 30 December, according to Lord Adonis, according to the Times.
This will give him a detailed road map of the next planned stage of the high-speed rail network.
The new line, which is to link London with the West Midlands, will run alongside urban areas and places where the impact on the environment is controversial, with a five-metre loop.
In the open terrain, the plan will show the concept within 25 metres of the final track.
HS2 is also to create three options for a larger, north-bound high-speed rail network.
Lord Adonis will respond to this in the spring.
The preferred proposed option is a Y-shaped route, where a single high-speed line would lead to the West Midlands.
The route would split in or near Birmingham and one branch would lead west of the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and another in a northeasterly direction to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line would lead to Scotland.
"It seems to be the best working option", said a railway insider.
Once completed, the travel time between London and Edinburgh would be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first section, which would not open until 2025, would allow travellers to cover the London-Birmingham route in 49 minutes, compared with just over an hour today.
The designs will allow trains to run at speeds of 400 km/h, making the British rail network the fastest in Europe.
The first line was planned to accommodate 400-metre trains with a maximum capacity of 1,100 passengers.
Up to 18 trains per hour could be operated on the London-Birmingham route.
This would mean that a terminal in London would be needed, capable of handling 20,000 passengers per hour.
Given the spatial constraints in the capital, it is expected that an existing station will be expanded to accommodate the high-speed network.
Railway experts say only St Pancras International or Euston has that potential.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he thinks this plan should be continued, but the lengthy public consultation and planning means that a final decision will not be made until after the general election.
But even if he sets the wheels in motion, the rail network will have to be built in sections.
The trains would first have to switch from the high-speed lines to existing lines north of Birmingham, which would keep the travel time between London and Scotland at over three hours.
This is seen as a crucial tipping point to ensure a shift from air to rail, a stepping stone to the railway revolution.
Taxpayers are coming for a mortgage for 75,000 pounds of a conservative's orangery.
Alan Duncan, the leading Conservative MP, has been charging the taxpayer thousands of pounds a year for the cost of an orange grove he built in his home in his constituency.
The party's prison spokesman, who was demoted by David Cameron for complaining that members of the House of Commons had to live on "meager rations", has increased his mortgage by £75,000 to build a oak-framed farmhouse on his second home in Rutland.
He was allowed to charge the taxpayer the additional interest, a sum of hundreds of pounds a month.
The House of Commons approved the motions at the time and they were not questioned by Sir Thomas Legg, who is conducting a review of the expenditure of the House of Commons Members.
Duncan, one of the wealthiest members of the House of Commons, owns a two-storey house in a village in his constituency of Rutland and Melton.
Nearby houses have been sold for almost a million pounds (1.1 million euros).
The ground floor includes kitchen, living and dining rooms, but the Fee's Office, a spending control unit of the House of Commons, has agreed that Duncan needs more space.
Last year he planted a winter garden, which the plans call "orangerie".
Neighbors described it as a "glass house for entertainment".
Mr Duncan was also not asked to comment on the increased borrowing during a recent review of his previous mortgage contracts by the Standards and Privileges Committee.
The Committee cleared him of any irregularities last month after examining his expenditure.
In 2004, Duncan transferred the security for a mortgage of £271,406 (€300,000) from his London home to his constituency house, which he had bought in 1991, one year before his election as an MP.
Documents released this week show that by March of last year, Duncan was getting about 1,400 pounds a month in mortgage payments.
In April, his claims rose to more than £1,800 a month.
The interest rate on Duncan RBS's mortgage has not changed during this period, suggesting that the overall increase was used to finance the withdrawal of £75,000 (EUR 85,000).
The normal non-adjusted RBS rate fell from 7.94 per cent in December 2007 to 4 per cent in March this year, where it still stands.
The latest documents released by the House of Commons show that Duncan continued to claim his right to £1,250 a month in May.
Duncan lost his position as House Leader of the Opposition in September after an undercover reporter filmed him saying that MPs were "living on meager rations" after the spending scandal.
"Basically, working for the state means you have to live on meager rations and be treated like a ****".
He said: "I have spent my money on my garden, and I claim a small share of it.
And I could have demanded the whole damn sum, but I'm not doing it".
The MP, a millionaire from his former career as an oil wholesaler, was first attacked in May over his spending when it became clear that he had demanded thousands of pounds for his garden before he had cleared with the Fees Office that this "could be considered an exaggerated demand".
An activist has dug a hole in Duncan's lawn in the shape of a pound sign in protest after it became known that he had demanded 4,000 pounds over three years.
When asked about the increased mortgage last night, Duncan said, "This was approved by both the Fee's Office and subsequently by Legg for the increase".
He added: "There is no debate about dodging and overriding or bending the rules or anything like that.
Everything is perfectly transparent and strictly within the rules, is approved and everything.
It couldn't be cleaner and clearer".
Come, all you devotees, to admire Brighton's beach huts advent calendar
Brighton beach huts have found a new life for the winter months as an interactive Advent calendar.
