The separatist Abkhazia has elected its president, Georgia denounces it as a "putsch".
Abkhazia elected its president on Saturday, a little more than a year after Moscow recognized the pro-Russian separatist Georgian region as independent, Tbilisi denounced the "strike".
Some 131,000 people were called to participate in the first election after the August 2008 Russo-Georgian war for control of South Ossetia, another Georgian secessionist territory recognized by Russia.
The polling stations closed at 5pm GMT.
Voter turnout was about 58% a few hours before the polls closed, according to the Abkhaz election commission officials.
The first preliminary results were to be announced on the night of Saturday to Sunday.
The five candidates, including former President Serguei Bagapch, categorically reject the idea of reunification with Georgia, which condemns the election.
This election is a farce.
The European Union has also been involved in the negotiations with the countries of Central and Eastern Europe.
Besides Russia, only Nicaragua and Venezuela have recognised the independence of this area of 216,000 inhabitants, while the rest of the world perceives it as part of Georgia, which is illegally occupied by Russia.
After separating from Georgia during the 1992-93 conflict, in which several thousand people died, Abkhazia wants to prove by this election that it is ready to join the international community.
This process is a stage in our new life, a new era as an independent state, explained Svetlana Kvartchia, a 54-year-old historian who claims to have voted for Mr Bagapch.
She was one of the voters who went to vote in a polling station located in a school in the capital city of Soukhoumi, a beautiful white building with a few palm trees in front of the entrance.
The question of Russian dominance is at the heart of this presidential election, in a region with beautiful landscapes on the Black Sea.
Large signs showing Bagapch with Russian President and Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev and Vladimir Putin are all over this small area of 216,000 inhabitants.
In Gali, in the east of the country, the district chief, Beslan Archba, prepared a warm welcome for the Russian representatives who have come to monitor the election process.
We, the Abkhaz people, are grateful, he said at a small celebration, in reference to Moscow's support, particularly in the decision to recognize Abkhazia's independence.
I hope your country will soon be recognized by the United Nations, said Alexei Ostrovski, a member of the Russian parliament, raising a glass of vodka.
The opposition, represented by the former vice-president and two Russian businessmen, Zaous Ardzinba and Beslan Boutba, has criticized the agreements reached with Moscow last year, including the one in which Abkhazia leaves Russia control of the railway for 10 years.
The fifth candidate, Vitali Banba, claims to support neither the current government nor the opposition.
A majority of 50% plus one vote is necessary to win the election.
If none of the candidates reaches this threshold, a second round of voting must be organised within two weeks.
