According to Chatel, the geography and history subjects are reinforced by the school reform of the lycées.
In an interview published in the Sunday newspaper "Journal du dimanche", Luc Chatel, the national minister for education, stated that geography and history were to be reinforced by the school reform of the lycées, even though they were not compulsory in the terminale (year 12).
"Premiere students (grade 11) now have the same programme every four hours", Mr Chatel confirms.
The Minister said that "this hypocrisy must be overcome", because according to him "the scientific profile is no longer a scientific profile" but, on the whole, a concentration of "the best students".
"The socio-economic and literary profile (ES and L) must not become a sub-profile of the scientific", he continued, stressing: "I have not heard many historians and intellectuals who have complained about the lack of historical-geographical education in the technical lycées".
On Saturday, an IFOP poll published in Humanité showed that almost seven out of ten French people (69%) criticize the government's project to eliminate compulsory history and geography lessons in Terminale S (12th grade with a scientific profile), which was also criticized by many teachers and intellectuals, as well as the left and some representatives of the right.
The Minister replied that there was no question of limiting the philosophy of the S-terminal programme.
Luc Chatel also defended the reform of teacher education, while 16 organisations (students and trade unions) had called for a protest on Tuesday against the project, which they believe is a victim of the educational training of future teachers.
The Minister explained that they undergo a subject-specific aptitude test at the beginning of the year in Master 2 (M2) and an admission test at the end of the year, which tests their teaching skills.
They also conduct internships during the year at M2 and then teach in front of the pupils as internship teachers for a year.
He went on to say: "If you add up all the internships you have done before the test, you get even more hours than you spent in front of the students, which is more than 300 hours".
The minister finally stated that he wanted to offer "the individual right to education" - something "that does not exist in the education system".
He reiterated his intention to abolish the school card "by 2012".
15 minutes for the climate at the Ecole Normale Supérieure
Fifteen minutes to talk about the effort at the Copenhagen Summit: this is the challenge Jean Jouzel, Vice-President of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, had to tackle on Saturday morning at the Ecole Normale Supérieure in the rue d'Ulm in Paris.
As an AFP journalist noted, Nobel Peace Prize winner Jean Jouzel opened the first of the "Ernest" conferences, where experts address the public with fifteen-minute film contributions.
"We want to do something that will reach people and make them want to learn more", said Edouard Hannezo, 22, one of the organizers of the event, on the sidelines of the conference, which was named after the fish in the school's swimming pool.
"Around 20 participants were selected from the experts, also according to their charisma", he explains.
"You can talk about global warming for hours, but you can also explain the core goals in a few minutes", Jean Jouzel told AFP, speaking freely to about 50 people using only footage.
"This is part of our role as scientists", he stressed, hoping that the audience would learn from this that "the Copenhagen conference is based on an absolutely serious scientific dossier".
The videos of these conferences will be available online on the school's website from 15 December.
The next "Ernest" day is scheduled for February and will be held every two months thereafter.
Late payment: angry prison guards, action planned
The unions of law enforcement officers have called for a general day of action on Friday to ensure that the premiums and overtime, which were postponed until January for budgetary reasons, are paid before the Christmas holidays.
The second union of prison officers (FO-Pénitentiaire) called on non-employees to demonstrate in front of the prison on Tuesday morning and block it to draw attention to the "theft of what is theirs".
The third, the CGT Penitentiary, called for "a strong mobilisation in the various prisons" which condemned the non-payment of overtime, overnight allowances and Sunday and holiday allowances in December as "disgraceful and unacceptable".
The first union of prison officers, the Autonomous Federal Penitentiary Union (UFAP/UNSA), called for "general mobilizations . . . to show discontent and anger".
The head of the Penal Service and the Ministry of Justice stated that overtime had increased sharply in 2009 and not all of it was budgeted, but they guarantee that the remaining claims will be paid in January.
