The manager revolution or the end of strategic early education?
If nothing changes in the leadership of the great French companies our struggle for the development of economic intelligence has been in vain ...
For over a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies in relation to its employees, said the position of the company vis-à-vis the consumers before the marketing revolution: It is for the staff to join "values" determined to impose the best, as it was formerly on the consumer products designed by the technicians in the factory.
By putting the customer at the heart of the enterprise, the marketing revolution has given the strategies of conquering the markets in place... despite the authoritarian temptation to impose separate products on the customer's preferences again on a regular basis!
A demobilization of the staff can lead to a fatal demoralization.
The suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of a much larger phenomenon that affects employees in particular.
This demobilization has a negative impact on the development of all intellectual functions of the enterprise, in particular those of R & D and, more importantly, those of economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EI (Economic Intelligence) "requires all parties involved (...) to take a proactive approach and to take a forward-looking view"; it demands from employees a commitment which is completely contrary to the instructions of the authoritarian management.
That is why we are calling for an operational revolution that puts employees at the centre of the company's concerns, alongside customers.
The very limited benefits of internal surveys
Will internal surveys, such as the questionnaire that Orange has submitted to its employees, spark this revolution in management practice?
I'm afraid not.
- First, because I could see that the whole structure, in the face of a new situation, after many detours, eventually comes to do first and foremost what it always did.
It is also because authoritarianism - one of the pathologies of power - increases in proportion to the magnitude of its own failures.
And finally, because most leaders have a highly simplified view of human behavior.
Their interpretation of psychology, which originated in the great engineering schools, is mechanistic.
They are adopting, by intellectual convenience, the old behaviorist theory that was recently reactivated by American "neuroscience" and unwittingly spread widely by research institutes and by the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to apply the "lever" (sic) to employee engagement, a recent survey by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reinforces managers' attitude towards a mechanistic control system unsuited to today's world.
Identifying and measuring the mobilisation factors
Instead, the operational revolution necessary for the smooth functioning of modern enterprises requires the adoption of a definitive view of human behaviour.
It is to integrate a basic protocol into every management thought or practice: for employees, commitment to the enterprise is only possible if it clearly appears as a means of achieving part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
At present, only the studies on multifunctional analysis adopt this concept of employee motivation.
These studies have shown that they assess their company on the basis of a predetermined doxa, which allows them to assess what it offers them to achieve their life goals through their perceived image of the company.
By identifying and measuring these mobilizing factors, business leaders can monitor, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and put their human resource management back in place.
They thus create a fertile ground for the coordinated development of robust and efficient economic intelligence.
Oslo speech: "Just War" brings praise to Obama from the right
The American right on Friday welcomed Barack Obama's speech in Oslo the night before and was pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize had defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
Conservatives who had mocked Obama's award on October 9th applauded the president's speech, following the example of former vice presidential candidate Sarah Palin in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said, explained Palin, the face of the right wing of the Republican Party in the daily newspaper USA Today, adding that she herself had raised the subject of a "sometimes necessary" war in her subsequently published memoirs.
War is, of course, the last thing I think the Americans want to do, but it's necessary.
She says we have to stop the terrorists down there.
Obama, who inherited two wars from his predecessor George W. Bush, the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, tried to justify the use of force in Oslo on Thursday, a way of explaining his decision nine days ago to send 30,000 additional troops to Afghanistan.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, expressed the opinion that the president had done "a very good job" in Oslo.
I thought the speech was really good, the former speaker of the House of Representatives was delighted, who especially acknowledged the reference to "the existence of evil in the world" in Obama's words.
In some parts, I felt that this speech was entirely historic, explained Ginrich, who was interviewed on the radio programme "The Takeaway".
The former lawmaker, who is seen by some as a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, said he was pleased to see a "leftist president" reminding members of the Nobel Committee that they "are not free and cannot award a peace prize if there is no use of force".
Michael Gerson, former George W. Bush writer and now Washington Post editor, said Obama delivered "a very American speech".
In addition to presenting himself as a "cosmopolitan", as "he always does", he spoke "like an American president" when he pointed out that Europeans "live in a security bubble that they did not create themselves and do not do much to protect", Gerson said.
Among the few leftists who are not convinced, former UN ambassador John Bolton, a Bush-era falcon, described the speech on the National Review Online website as "boring, haughty and uninspiring".
To the left of the president, Democratic Representative Dennis Kucinich is concerned about Barack Obama's defense of the military.
If the war is covered up with justice, the massacre of the innocent can be easily justified, he warns.
The moderate left press, however, continues to praise the President.
The Los Angeles Times, which still considers Obama to be the early recipient of the Nobel Prize, called the speech itself "a monumental achievement" for a speaker as talented as he is.
The Oslo speech "provides a blueprint for guiding international decisions against conflict, poverty and oppression", says the California daily.
The New York Times believes Obama "proclaimed the necessary discourse" and calls his speech "both bleak and exemplary".
Long-distance drivers: Three marathons for a deal to secure supply at Christmas
After a three-week marathon of negotiations, the unions of the street association and the TLF - the only employers' organisation to stay until the end - reached an agreement on Friday evening, ending the strike order and the threat of severe supply shortages at Christmas.
At the signing session on Friday evening, the Secretary of State for Transport, Dominique Bussereau, 'welcomed' the agreement, which was initiated on Wednesday morning after weeks of negotiations.
After a second night of negotiations, the negotiators parted early on Friday morning, hoping to sign the agreement quickly by late in the morning.
This was despite the fact that the three employers' associations (FNTR, Unostra and OTRE) had left the meeting angry.
However, it was still more than six hours from the start of the meeting at 11 a.m. until the conclusion of the agreement and it was not until 6 p.m. that the agreement was signed.
The conflict "would have caused a great deal of damage to the companies" and "it was feared that it would affect the holidays at the end of the year", said Bussereau.
The agreement provides for a 4% increase in wages for the lowest wage groups (local and regional road transport) and a 2.9% increase for the highest wage groups (international transport).
The hourly rate for workers with the lowest wages rises from 8.72 to 9.06 euros.
"It's not much, but we're starting small", said Patrice Clos (FO).
The activists are now being told to stop blocking the supply centers.
"However, there will probably always be some dissenters who are not satisfied with the agreement", he adds.
The TLF chairman, Philippe Grillot, described the agreement as "good", although it was "difficult to accommodate these wage increases in the face of international competition".
He said the increase was €170 per month for the low-wage groups and €100 to €120 per month for the high-wage groups.
'This agreement is based on common sense and respect for employees,' said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) described it as 'a historic agreement'.
The Commission's proposal for a directive on the protection of workers from the risks of exposure to radioactive substances and their residues is based on the principle of subsidiarity.
The agreement also provides for a 3% increase in travel costs and the maintenance of the overall road transport charge in the first half of 2010, which will allow in particular to address the issue of the 13th monthly salary and the modernisation of collective agreements.
Mr Bussereau recalled that "the reduction of employer taxes of EUR 100 million" was the subject of a government amendment to the revised Finance Bill for 2009, which was passed by the National Assembly on the night of Thursday to Friday.
The government is demanding an "identical" vote from the Senate.
The signature of the TLF allows the agreement to be applied initially to the companies affiliated to this organisation and then, in the event of an extension by the Minister of Labour, to the whole profession.
This will be the case "in the shortest possible time", assures Bussereau.
The opposition of the employers' associations can only delay the procedure.
The FNTR denounced a "fraudulent trade" because the €100 million "had already been promised to the sector to compensate for part of the carbon tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate as quickly as possible, not on the basis of a common analysis, but in order not to discourage the goose-eaters on the approaching Christmas days, complained Unostra.
The agreement threatens to "grave a grave for small and medium-sized enterprises in the sector over the next 12 months", according to the Otre Association.
The Commission has also been asked to submit a proposal for a directive on the protection of workers from the risks of exposure to radioactive substances.
