Turkey's Constitutional Court dissolves pro-Kurdish party, decision with serious consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court announced on Friday the dissolution of the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that was immediately followed by angry demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision threatens to make the work of the government, which is trying to reach out to the Kurdish community to end the 25-year conflict, extremely difficult.
The "Democratic Society Party" (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "place for activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity", President of the Constitutional Court Hasim Kiliç told the press four days after the decision.
According to Kiliç, the decision was taken unanimously by 11 judges, requiring a majority of seven votes to enforce the dissolution.He also pointed out that 37 of the party's leaders, including chairman Ahmet Türk and parliamentarian Aysel Tugluk, were excluded from political activities for five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Türk and Tugluk and the confiscation of the party's assets.
The DTP now has 21 seats in the Parliament (out of 550).
The party leaders expressed their opinion before the verdict that the MPs would rather leave Parliament than act as non-party MPs.
The decision follows a 2007 case brought by the Turkish Federal Prosecutor Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accused the DTP of following the "instructions" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which is considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and numerous other countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party claims to have "no links" with the PKK, but refuses to label it a terrorist organisation and calls on the government to negotiate.
The ruling by the Constitutional Court has put the government in the middle, which is seeking to meet the Kurdish community and to propose a series of measures to strengthen the rights of the Kurds in order to eradicate Kurdish support for the PKK and put an end to the conflicts.
The DTP leaders reiterate that a dissolution could lead to a resurgence of tensions in southeastern Anatolia, where numerous demonstrations against the detention conditions of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan in recent weeks have led to clashes with the police.
Since the court's announcement, thousands of protesters have gathered outside the DTP premises in the south-eastern city of Diyarbakir, which is predominantly populated by Kurds.
Law enforcement officers used tear gas grenades and water cannons as protesters began throwing Molotov cocktails and stones.
Hundreds of people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
Following the verdict, Türk expected the court's decision to "further deepen the despair".
"Turkey cannot clarify this (Kurdish, ed.) issue by banning a party", he told the press.
The government, which is composed of a party that emerged from the Islamist movement, also regretted the decision.
"We are opposed in principle to the closure of the parties.
This does not solve the problems", said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
"This decision is a torpedo on the democratic opening that has been promoted by the government", said political market observer Ahmet Insel.
"It is obvious that we can prepare for a reaction from the PKK", he adds.
On Thursday, the PKK confessed to an attack that three days earlier had killed seven soldiers in northern Turkey, one of the most brutal attacks in recent months.
