The cradle of the dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The two-meter-long, five-foot-tall animal walked on two powerful hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws, and a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it wouldn't be anything special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs to display these physical features, report Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in the journal Science on Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangea on the equator.
Tawa opens a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It tells us a lot about the relationships, distribution, and characteristics of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavating at the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We've sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in a day, which is unprecedented for Triassic deposits, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by the researchers as new species.
During the excavation, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
Find confirms theories about early dinosaur history
The name "Tawa" comes from the Hopi sun god.
Sterling Nesbitt says that this is an extraordinary discovery: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only found in fragments".
Other dinosaur experts don't necessarily share that enthusiasm.
This discovery is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current theory, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these dinosaurs is often controversial.
For example, experts debate when lizards split into their three main lineages: the carnivorous theropods, which later included Tyrannosaurus rex, Velociraptor, and also the birds, the four-legged sauropods known as "long-necks", and their relatives, and the plant-eating ornithischia, which included the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced features, says Nesbitt.
For example, on the skull of Tawa hallae, researchers found evidence of air sacs, like those of the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air sacs, birds breathe more efficiently than mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were also apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air sacs, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of giant sauropods later also had air sacs and lightweight bones, the common ancestor of both groups probably had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the earliest known dinosaurs lived in South America, researchers conclude that lizards first appeared there.
Thus, the three development lines separated early and spread from South America to all parts of the world, which at that time still formed a single land mass as the supercontinent Pangea.
The team, along with Tawa Hallae, found the remains of two other theropods not closely related to each other.
The researchers argue that the three cannot be descended from a common immigrant ancestor.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the Science study.
There are, of course, contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which is a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in what is now Poland, says Bonn-based paleontologist Martin Sander.
His view may be distorted, for South America is simply home to a remarkable number of primitive dinosaur fossils, while on other continents there is hardly anything to be found.
How dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare side line of the reptilian lineage to the dominant land vertebrates of the Middle Ages is still a mystery.
During the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, including the ancestors of modern-day crocodiles and flying sauries, and numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread around the world, developing many new species, while the relatives on the border from the Triassic to the Jurassic became extinct.
Success stories did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass extinction event, which the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact helped a group of animals that had also evolved in the Triassic to flourish, and since then a shadow being has been born: the mammals.
