The new Silicon Valley
For years, it was considered a secret city, inaccessible to Western visitors.
Selenograd, one of the ten districts of the capital city of Moscow, was a heavily guarded site for secret arms research in the Soviet Union.
Today, the commune of 216,000 inhabitants, located 23 miles [37 km] from the center of Moscow, is known as "Russia's Silicon Valley".
Important research and production facilities for micro and nanoelectronics are located here.
Since September 2008, representatives of Selenograd had established contacts with the Frankfurt science centre Riedberg - with the university institutes and the companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
The Commission has also been involved in the implementation of the European Union's external relations policy.
Moscow's deputy mayor Yuri Rosljak and Selenograd's prefect Anatoly Smirnov led the Russian delegation, while Frankfurt's planning director Edwin Schwarz signed off.
In 2010, representatives of the FIZ and small and medium-sized enterprises in the scientific research area will travel to Selenograd for a seminar.
Scientific exchanges
It is a continuous scientific exchange.
But it is also about economic relations.
FIZ firms will be able to gain a foothold in the growing Russian market.
On the contrary, Russian scientific companies want to get contracts in Germany.
Selenograd is home to important Russian research institutes and companies.
These include the Moscow Institute of Electronic Technology, the large companies Citronics and Rosssijskaja Elektronika.
The commune was founded in 1958 as a so-called "socialist planned city" for arms research.
Selenograd (literally translated "green city") got its name from the forested hilly landscape in which the research facilities are embedded.
