The dream world
Some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
It is not only the mentally ill and the drug addicted who blur the lines between imagination and reality.
As long as it happens in your sleep, everything's fine.
When we lie in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we are free to indulge in the wildest imaginations and fantasies.
However, in the modern Western world, those who experience dreamlike states while awake, seeing and hearing things that others do not see or hear, are usually considered to be insane or drug addicts, at least a freak.
But such images and voices are not just produced by the mentally ill or by drug addicts.
It's our imagination that's to blame: the same neural processes that enable us to design houses, paint pictures, or write novels sometimes blur the lines between dream, delusion, and reality.
Dreamy altered states of consciousness can take many forms, at best we call them visions, at worst, delusions.
Although the causes and effects may differ, visions of the mystic Hildegard of Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic raptures, psychosis, and hallucinations can be traced to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions occur when the balance of the brain's neuronal messengers - primarily dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin, and acetylcholine - is disturbed and the interaction of various parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts are very common during schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity has no power over him
The connection between delusions and dreams has intrigued philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle defined hallucinations as a form of waking dream, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 a "great similarity of madness with dream states", and Sigmund Freud even described dreams as "a psychosis, with all its dissonances, delusions, and delusions".
It's the fall of 2001, when Henning T. turns into a comic book character.
His body is two-dimensional and creaky.
Gravity has no power over him, he's floating on the ceiling.
He feels a kick.
Behind him, winged devils with blood-red, twisted scabs, teeth-splitting.
They chase him, kick him with heavy, flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels the pain all over his body.
Loud, vicious voices are ringing from the walls and the radio.
He can't stand them anymore, the voices that insult and insult him.
Henning T. pulls two cables from the stereo, knots them into a noose and attaches them to a hook on the ceiling.
He gets on a loudspeaker and puts the noose around his neck.
It jumps.
The noose is coming off.
"Go to the hospital and get cured!"
Henning T. is 40 years old today, he's had six acute psychosis episodes, the last two years ago, the first almost 20 years.
It was caused by LSD.
He's been diagnosed with schizoaffective paranoid psychosis, and he's also manic-depressive, taking medication for depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He's learned to live with his illness, and he's been married for three years.
In the psychosis, he says, I experienced the worst fear and the deepest despair.
The illusions are cruel reality
About one percent of the population develops schizophrenia at least once in their lifetime, and it is the second most common disorder treated in psychiatric hospitals after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, the sufferer is often unable to distinguish between the internal and the external world, and becomes over-excited, which can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, delusions of relationship or delusions of pursuit.
Especially common is the practice of hearing voices - voices that command, comment, or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are not uncommon.
The person is unable to distinguish the important from the unimportant, the brain is unable to filter out disturbing signals, and the mind is flooded with impressions.
Like dreams, psychosis opens the floodgates to ideas and fantasies that come from deeper layers of consciousness.
Reality perception in psychosis is subjective, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician at the General Psychiatry Clinic at the University Hospital of Heidelberg.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the action, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he becomes passive, he is overwhelmed by events, as in a dream, and he cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenics therefore often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
They are often unable to reconcile reality, the illusions are cruel reality, no waking up.
Having a hallucination once in your life.
Unlike in dreams, says Fuchs, "the sensory and spatial structure of reality perceived in psychosis is basically preserved".
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of experience takes place in the real frame.
Why our brains make capriolets is still a mystery to researchers.
Exceptional circumstances can cause anyone to lose his sense of reality for a short time, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that genes are not the only determining factor.
Researchers believe that the brain damage is minimal.
We suspect that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development, by a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, for example, explains Fuchs.
But how the disruption of the neural system occurs remains a mystery, and it does not manifest itself at all for many years.
Environmental factors also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be triggers for psychosis if the mood is present.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also cause psychosis, as they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brains are hot
The crazy thing is that psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, while others spend money on drugs to get them, says psychology professor Erich Kasten of Lübeck.
Whether illusions are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often a matter of opinion.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and delusions for ten years, and last year he evaluated his findings in the book The Unreal World in Our Mind.
Hallucinations are a typical symptom of psychosis, but they are also a symptom of a surprising number of other disorders.
These often include mental disorders such as borderline or depression, as well as diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's, and traumatic brain injury.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, even the brains of healthy people hallucinate.
Hallucinations, like boxes, are made up of memory contents that are usually withheld.
They occur when areas of the brain that process sensory perception are overactive or under-inhibited, when our brains are running hot or when we lack stimulation.
Drugs can cause this condition just as much as brain damage or psychosis.
But also withdrawal from stimulation, stress, love or other mental states.
In recent studies, up to a third of those interviewed reported experiencing a hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. is 16 years old, lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends the high school there.
A normal girl, actually.
If it weren't for the pictures and the voices.
During the break, a slender boy with long, dark hair may approach it.
When he answers, the classmates look at him in surprise - no one else sees or hears this boy.
You think the shy girl is a wild daydreamer, but Sarah K. isn't dreaming, she knows that.
She's awake, she hears and sees this boy, just like she hears and sees the girl in the bank next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for moments.
It's a good feeling she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? She sometimes asks herself.
But she knows that this boy and the other illusions aren't real and they're gone.
At night the apparitions are usually frightening
Often the illusion is also a burden.
When she is in the classroom, she may not be able to follow the material because the teacher is presenting a new student to her eyes and ears while explaining mathematical equations audibly and visually to everyone else at the table.
At night, the apparitions are usually frightening.
When she waits in her dark room for sleep, which comes far too seldom and far too late, she often cannot tell whether she is awake or dreaming, whether the images she sees, the scratches or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, are coming before her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, she's yelling at the figures.
She won't tell her parents or friends, they'll think she's crazy.
Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She graduated from high school last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Since she contacted psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she knows for sure she's not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art from despair
If a person is socially isolated or suffers from deprivation of arousal, he is likely to have hallucinations after a while, says Kasten.
I suspect the brain is under-occupied and is self-entertaining.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she was 13 years old, when she learned that the man she's called "daddy" since she can remember is not her biological father.
Because visual and acoustic hallucinations involve the same brain regions that process real impressions and sounds, people like Sarah K. have difficulty distinguishing between illusions and reality. "Every experience", says Kasten, "is in the brain, where reality is formed.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain creates, which is why they seem so real".
Even nightly dreams are viewed by the box as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their illusions as unreal.
Therefore, Dr. Kaster advises his patients to value hallucinations as a special ability.
Borderline between dream and hallucination
In our world, which is too conscious, imaginary experiences are unfortunately often pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician at the Florence-Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a serious, painful disease, but it also has positive, creative aspects - insanity is also a work of art from despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has been exploring what's called the oneiroid form of experience, a particular form of dream-altered waking consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams that the experiencer considers real and that he cannot distinguish from waking reality even afterwards.
The oneiroid state of consciousness is created in extreme situations caused by trauma or disease, for example in polyradiculosis patients who experience motor paralysis while fully conscious.
If a person is threatened with loss of self and world, such as permanent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening reality with his own, imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
It's kind of like the border between a dream and a hallucination.
Since it is not possible to deal with a situation in reality, a change in the world takes place, but the reality is represented in the imagination.
An intense form of meaning-making and meaning-giving in an inherently intolerable situation, which allows us human beings our own creative capacity not to sink into a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his Oneiroid experiences in his book "Heart Changes" as a salvation of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after a heart valve operation followed by a heart transplant, while his body is condemned to immobility in the intensive care unit.
Claussen is immersed in a self-created world, visiting strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden old man, on board a train sanatorium, with a robot watching over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages amongst nobles who make intoxicants out of blood.
He's being dragged by a Greek on a motorcycle back to his homeland, surfing in the snow of the Alps with his hospital bed, and he meets a Korean mobster.
He's completely absorbed in the imagined events, everything is real, even later in the memory.
These inner journeys are fundamentally different for Claussen than any other dream.
Dreaming is a different state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories of mental travel are still vivid in me, years later, in subtle details.
More vivid and intense than even what you actually experience.
The intensity of this experience pushes the horizon of our other life experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oneiroids, psychosis, hallucinations, and drug addiction show how fragile our inner images of the outer reality are.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a distortion of what we call reality".
It is an experience that can be rewarding.
