75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the conclusion of the study "Fertility and Career of Women in Spain", carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 makes this clear: 75% of working women see their career opportunities on the labour market restricted by motherhood.
The study reveals that there are large differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether the women work or not and, if so, what kind of occupation they have.
Those who do no other work outside the home, work only part-time or have no fixed employment contract are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with permanent jobs, especially in the public sector, are delaying the start of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"Women in the 35-49 age group with a permanent job do not have their first child until 3.7 years after moving in on average, a figure that rises to 4.1 years for women with a permanent job who took longer to achieve this and who did not move in and have their first child until much later.
Moreover, the nature of work has a major influence on motherhood, although less than the calendar in terms of readiness to conceive", explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor to be taken into account when it comes to the age of women at marriage and the birth of their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference was also observed among women of the same age.
For example, women in the 35-49 age group, whether they have only a primary or higher education, became mothers for the first time at an average of 25.1 or 32.1 years.
There is also a further difference between women according to their level of education.
While women with a bachelor's degree get married before their first job and have their first child, women with a secondary or higher education do the opposite, seeking a job and getting married and having their first child, Delgado notes.
