Support for braking manoeuvres in critical situations is now compulsory
As with the anti-lock braking system ABS and as is happening now with the stability control system ESP, the emergency braking assistance systems must become a compulsory feature in European cars.
In fact, they are already compulsory for all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, and a period of grace has been fixed for the remaining vehicles until the end of February 2011.
The European Union's action aims to improve pedestrian protection, but the way these braking systems work can also help to prevent many road accidents.
The purpose of the emergency braking assist is to apply more pressure to the brakes in the event of a critical braking manoeuvre, which the system detects by the braking force applied by the driver to the brake pedal.
However, this system does not exert this pressure to the end.
According to a study commissioned by the Bosch vehicle component manufacturer, one third of the drivers involved in an accident had not stepped on the brake pedal before the collision and half had not brake at full power.
Up to 1,100 accidents
Brake assist, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system, thus reducing the braking time and thus the braking distance a car travels during braking.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assist.
There would be even fewer accidents - one in four accidents involving injuries to persons could be prevented, it is estimated - once the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
The vehicle is then equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while applying a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system helps him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not react to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assistant applies maximum pressure on the brakes to keep the damage as low as possible.
