New programmes for the inspection of vehicles
In these days of storms and accidents, not only the car repair shops are earning
Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are hauled to the workshops, where an appraiser must assess the damage and the cost of repairs.
No accident is the same and calculating the cost of parts and hours can be a long and complicated task.
The calculation of the repair costs of between EUR 20 000 and EUR 30 000 per hand, including parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
But with the help of the latest computer tools, it is a matter of minutes.
That's why almost 100% of the appraisers use this type of system.
Accident assessment and repair service and application providers shall collect the information they receive from manufacturers in order to process it and provide it to their customers in the form of a useful programme.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American Solera group, is the market leader; 80% of all assessments are made with its products.
The other two companies competing in the market for tools for evaluation and reporting are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by the manufacturers is far from easy.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, Audatex's sales manager, the company works with 63 manufacturers and importers, each of whom provides the information in a different format.
Moreover, the amount of data to be processed is increasing, to the point that more versions, variants and motorizations have been launched in the last five years than in the previous 15 years.
As soon as a new car is launched, the companies start working.
It is a difficult task, since each of the thousands of vehicle parts has to be catalogued and its price entered.
In addition, each model creates an 'intelligent' graphic image on which different parts of the vehicle can be 'clicked'.
If the model is a big seller, the work can be completed in a week if the procedure proceeds quickly.
If the car is a less used one, it can take up to three or four months.
For example, they have information on the more exclusive models, such as Porsche models, but not Ferrari or Lamborghini.
The number of vehicles on the roads is over 99%.
For the purposes of documentation and database production, Audatex has eight centres around the world (Spain, France, Germany, USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), each of which is specialised in specific brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There are more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics) working simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests EUR 90 million annually in the development of these databases.
They're recording 2.5 million data each month, and their customers get the updates every other day.
The elaboration of this enormous flow of information enables companies to use it in different ways and thus to offer different products.
The most common use is for repairs and repair, but depending on the country there are also tools for managing scrap parts or calculating the fault or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that gives information on the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer this service in Spain, but in the United States.
A review of the products offered by Audatex provides an easy overview of the type of support it provides to industry experts.
This company offers ten different tools, the star of which is AudaPlus, a standard accident assessment solution for the appraisers.
It includes vehicles, motorcycles and light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the painting prices.
This tool is paid for according to its purpose, i.e. for each opinion.
The most expensive is for customers who use it rarely, up to 10 times a month, which is 5.75 euros per month.
But every insurance company that makes thousands of reports negotiates the price with Audatex.
Other products, such as AudaVIN, allow a vehicle and the equipment with which it was run off the assembly line to be fully identified by reference to the chassis number alone.
AudaGlass deals with the vehicle discs, and AudaSubastas is an internet service open to the specialist market, which can be used to offer services for vehicles declared to be in total damage.
Their statistical service is very useful for identifying trends, for carrying out geodemographic analyses or for obtaining information on variations by brand and model.
For example, it can be used to determine how many models of a particular car have had to be repaired due to breakdowns or how many of them have been involved in a serious accident in a given period of time.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of computer tools.
It also distributes GM Estimates, which is also intended for experts and likewise provides digital images, access to parts or prices and official working hours of the manufacturer.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa Group, which was founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of damage, breakdown or maintenance of vehicles.
The GT Guide for expert opinions is a reference product on the market.
They work with 24,000 users in workshops, 3,100 appraisers and 53 insurance companies.
Its turnover has increased by 20% per annum over the last three years, reaching EUR 10,8 million in 2008.
At the beginning of last year, they started to enter the international market with the opening of an office in Paris.
Audatex, on the other hand, was founded in Germany in 1966 and established in Spain in 1979.
According to company sources, 62% of its business is carried out in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America.
The total worldwide turnover of the Solera group (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) is $557 million, 3.35 more than in 2008.
In this country, the company has revenues of EUR 19.1 million, 7.2% more than in the previous year.
In 2005, the Solera Group was worth $1 billion on the stock exchange, and today its shares are trading at $2.4 billion.
Since 2007, they have been listed on the New York Stock Exchange and part of the Standard & Poor's benchmark index.
Internet auctioning of cars in bad condition
